In the former case, this assumes two events in 10 years of use with exposure of 10% of the world’s falciparum malaria (Burgess &Young 1959; Martin&Arnold1968; Looareesuwan et al. 1996; Su et al. 1997 and ignores the relevant research that shows the gradual evolution of resistance to malaria as document in various research papers:Pooja Mittra, Sumiti Vinayak, Hina Chandawat, Manoj K. Das, Neeru Singh, Sukla Biswas, Vas Dev, Ashwani Kumar, Musharraf A. Ansari, and Yagya D. Sharma, Progressive Increase in Point Mutations Associated with Chloroquine Resistance in Plasmodium falciparum Isolates from IndiaVolume 193(2006), pages 1304 1312For more details, see Nick Matzke's contribution http://www.pandasthumb.org/archives/2007/10/full-text-of-th.html
